&lt;div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Teknowlogy Group Opinion&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p &gt;Key findings&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For this C&amp;amp;SI for IoT Solutions RADAR, in which we will provide a detailed analysis of providers’ connected vehicle portfolios, strategies and strengths, we selected 23 major providers from a list of over 30 suitable candidates. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Quite generally, we see a rather heterogeneous landscape of top players in the area of connected vehicles, mainly consisting of large international and traditional IT services and technology companies. Interestingly, we can also find a few engineering and telecommunication companies in their ranks. Even though this RADAR has a specific focus on Europe, five Indian providers were able to position themselves among the 23 top companies (HCL Technologies, Infosys, TCS, Tech Mahindra, Wipro).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Among these 23 companies with advanced C&amp;amp;SI capabilities in the connected vehicle space, we identified six players to be “Best in Class”: Accenture, IBM, DTAG/T-Systems, Harman, Atos and Altran. These six “Best in Class” companies have been found outstanding in terms of providing a highly standardized set of C&amp;amp;SI services.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The top reference customers of the “Best in Class” players are often the leading automotive and truck manufacturers (e.g. BMW, Daimler, MAN, Volkswagen) as well as the leading suppliers in this space (e.g. Bosch, Continental, Schaeffler).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While most of the evaluated providers usually cover only one or two types of vehicle, the six leaders have a broader portfolio and cover cars, trucks or trains, for example. As of today, there is only a limited number of IoT centers or labs specifically dedicated to the connected vehicle topic in Europe. Particularly the providers headquartered outside of Europe do not have a very strong focus on the European market.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Due to this RADAR being focused on the European market, some of the international players with a weaker footprint in Europe (e.g. HCL Technologies) have received a less favorable ranking than would have been the case if their IoT or connected vehicle capabilities had been considered from a global perspective.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
