&lt;!--CONCLUSION--&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Teknowlogy Group Opinion&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p &gt;Key findings&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Most of the large global IT service providers as well as consultancies and even some of the industrial players provide consulting and system integration services in the digital factory context today. From a list of more than 40 players active in this field, we selected 23 that are most relevant in the European market and conducted an in-depth analysis of their strategies, portfolios and capabilities in the digital factory space.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To deliver IoT consulting and system integration services to the industrial sector, deep knowledge and expertise in terms of production and intra-logistic processes in various sub-industries are key.  We identified three groups of providers: IT services providers, management consulting firms and manufacturers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol style=&quot;padding-left:30px&quot;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The IT service providers are established C&amp;amp;SI players that have for long focused on the specific requirements of manufacturing companies' IT service requirements and have built significant and broad domain expertise. Most notable here are Accenture, Capgemini, IBM and Atos, who combine business and IT consulting, technology and systems integration expertise as well as digital technology (IoT) capabilities. With this very comprehensive set of capabilities, all four companies have achieved a “Best in Class” ranking.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The manufacturers positioned as providers of digital factory C&amp;amp;SI services have strong expertise in this area as well, even though their services portfolios have less granularity than those of the IT services providers. Nevertheless, Siemens managed to secure a “Best in Class” ranking (the only manufacturer in this category); ABB and Bosch were positioned as “Excellent”. All three have a long history in technology manufacturing and, on the basis of this industrial know-how as well as in-depth domain expertise, have developed IoT-related C&amp;amp;SI capabilities over the past few years on top of their products, whether they be hardware/machines or (to an increasing degree) software.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The management consultancies, such as BearingPoint, EY and Deloitte, also typically have established manufacturing and factory know-how as well as the resulting (management and business) consulting expertise, however they are less advanced (yet) in terms of IoT-related technology implementation capabilities. Still, they have achieved good rankings and are expected to advance further in future, above all due to the fact that they are (re)developing their integration services offering abandoned several years ago.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The digital factory will be one of the most interesting markets with a high growth potential for providers of IoT C&amp;amp;SI in the coming years, &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

