&lt;!--CONCLUSION--&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Teknowlogy Group Opinion&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p &gt;Key findings&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Even though transport is not the largest segment in terms of overall investments in software and IT services, it is definitely one of the most advanced when it comes to the adoption of IoT solutions. This results from increased operational cost pressure related to the maintenance of company fleets as well as fierce competition within the European transport market. The vendor landscape mostly consists of system integrators that are either generalists with a global footprint, specialists in the transport sector or vendors aspiring to expand their digital and system integration capabilities, e.g. management consultancies. For this RADAR report, we selected the 18 providers – from a list of more than 20 – with the most extensive portfolio of smart transport offerings, the strongest strategic focus in this area, notable use cases in Europe as well as a well-balanced mix of IT and consulting capabilities.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The principal finding is that there is a large-scale deployment of IoT solutions, far beyond the proof-of-concept stage, indicating both buyer companies’ technology readiness as well as maturity of the vendors’ offerings. The global and generalist system integrators, such as IBM or DXC Technology, occupy a prominent position within the smart transport segment. These vendors have considerable intellectual property and scale to deliver, coupled with a strong European presence and growing consulting and digital capabilities.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, some of the largest generalist vendors, e.g. Accenture, CGI, Atos or Capgemini, do not have a strong IoT value proposition for the transport sector, despite the strength of their general IT services offering in the transport sector. Other generalists, such as the India-centric vendors, do not have an extensive presence nor consulting capabilities in the European region. These factors explain the absence of these two types of players from the “Best in Class” category.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Good results were achieved by the system integrators that are smaller in scale, have a less pronounced geographic footprint and focus on fewer industries – one of them being transport. This applies e.g. to Indra, Lufthansa Industry Solutions (LHIND) and NIIT Technologies, all of which have a strategic focus on the transport industry, including highly focused value propositions and expertise.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;System integrators such as T-Systems or Orange Business Services, i.e. the IT services business units of some of Europe’s largest telecom operators, also have a very strong presence in the smart transport sector. This is mostly due to their early start in the IoT race, enabled by their parent companies, through which they could easily be provided with M2M connections. These connections are most suitable and easiest to deploy within moving vehicles and have thus been integrated by the players into their corresponding IoT solutions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And last but not least, “Excellent” rankings were awarded to the management consultancies with growing IT and digital capabilities, such as EY, which is particularly strong in strategic advice and organizational transformation – an expertise highly valued in large-scale IoT initiatives.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
