&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p &gt;In the following, the criteria for each provider that resulted in a substantial up- or downgrading as compared to the participating providers are set out. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;


&lt;!--CONCLUSION--&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Teknowlogy Group Opinion&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p &gt;Key findings&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Most of the large global IT service providers as well as consultancies are addressing the smart energy and resources sector. From a list of more than 25 energy-focused C&amp;amp;SI players, we selected 16 major providers within the European market for an in-depth analysis of their strategies, portfolio and capabilities in the smart energy &amp;amp; resources segment.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The players benchmarked here can broadly be divided into 3 groups: The IT service providers are established C&amp;amp;SI players that have long focused on the specific IT requirements of energy &amp;amp; resources companies and have built significant and broad domain expertise. Most notable here are Accenture, IBM, Atos and Capgemini, who can combine business and IT consulting, technology and systems integration expertise as well as digital technology (IoT) capabilities. With this very comprehensive set of capabilities, they were able to achieve the “Best in Class” ranking. It is interesting to see that three India-centric IT service players, Cognizant, TCS and Wipro, were able to position themselves successfully among the 16 top companies in the list. This fact illustrates that these companies are increasingly focusing their globally-built smart energy capabilities on the European market and will certainly be expanding their footprint further in the years to come.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The second group consists of two (industrial) technology companies, Siemens and ABB. They, too, have advanced C&amp;amp;SI capabilities in the smart E&amp;amp;R space and have been rated “Best in Class”. Siemens and ABB have evolved from a long history in energy technology manufacturing and, on the basis of their industrial know-how as well as in-depth domain expertise, have built up IoT-related C&amp;amp;SI capabilities over the past few years.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The third group of players is made up by the management consultancies, such as EY, BearingPoint or Deloitte. They have established energy sector know-how and the resulting (management and business) consulting expertise, but are less advanced (as of yet) in terms of IoT-related technology implementation capabilities. Still, they have achieved good rankings and are expected to advance further in future.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For this report, we have assessed the players based on the breadth and depth of their IoT C&amp;amp;SI capabilities in smart energy &amp;amp; resources. For companies to achieve a “Best in Class” ranking, we consider it important to have end-to-end capabilities ranging from consulting (deep domain expertise) over IoT-specific skills and solutions around IoT platforms to connectivity, security (especially in energy) and the capability to provide back-end integration (IoT solutions not being stand-alone).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Finally, akey finding of this RADAR analysis relates to the connection between smart energy and digital factory approaches. The energy and resources sector comprises a range of different companies, from oil &amp;amp; gas producers, mining companies, operators of nuclear power plants, producers of renewable energies (wind or solar farms, hydroelectric power stations) and distribution system operators to energy retail companies and other utilities (e.g. water suppliers). Across these different types of companies, IoT use cases are often quite similar to those seen in the manufacturing sector for “digital factory” approaches. Consequently, many of the players evaluated for smart E&amp;amp;R are similarly represented (and ranked) in our RADAR focused on the “digital factory” context.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
