&lt;div class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;
&lt;div&gt;

&lt;!--TITRE DOCUMENT--&gt;
&lt;h1 class=&quot;titre-document&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 40px;color: #41505D;margin: 0;line-height: inherit;&quot;&gt;C&amp;amp;SI services for IoT solutions Smart Retail &amp;amp;CPG&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When we talk about complex IoT projects, ICT and business decision makers are looking for consulting and systems integration partners with dedicated expertise in specific areas to implement a full IoT solution. teknowlogy provides transparency for buyers to identify the best partner for their complex IoT projects. We have to consider that C&amp;amp;SI services for IoT solutions serve different use cases. For this reason, teknowlogy uses different RADAR segments, dedicated to specific uses cases, to evaluate the providers of C&amp;amp;SI for IoT solutions in Europe. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Among the five available analysis segments, this document focuses on Smart Retail&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;CPG with the following definition.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Smart retail and CPG mean the implementation of digital devices, connectivity modules, hardware and software into the products, stores and warehouses to improve customer experience, customer loyalty, customer retention, in-store operations and warehouse management.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;section class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Use cases in the area of smart retail&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;CPG&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This part represents a list of relevant use cases in this context. The list is not exclusive and will be revised frequently. The main uses cases are as following:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Omni-channel sales, marketing&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;commerce (CX&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;IoT)&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Integration of retail channels (online, in-store, mobile) to enable diverse retail experiences. For example, a simple reorder button can be provided through a connectivity module in CPG products.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;Smart services (CPG) (CX&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;IoT)&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Integration of connectivity modules in CPG products to enable data collection on product usage and customer behavior via platforms or mobile apps connected with the product. This can be a new channel for the customer and enable new business models.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;Customer self-service (CX&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;IoT)&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In-store digital devices and apps help customers locate specific products, provide instant information on the items and offer self-service payment.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;Smart agents (CX&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;IoT)&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Smart agents and devices used to automate shopping or customer support; examples include connected buttons (dashes) for home-based shopping, AI agents and chat bots for customer support, in-store robots for welcoming customers, and providing product information.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;AR/VR headsets (CX&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;IoT)&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Headsets for virtual or augmented product/service experience can make it possible to look at various products in store or even at home.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;Smart tracking (IoT)&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The use of environmental sensors and connectivity modules (RFID, WiFi, beacons, Bluetooth, etc.) to detect movement, temperature, noise or to create heat maps can be used for the analysis of store operations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;Smart delivery (CX&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;IoT)&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Use of connected vehicles and connectivity modules to improve and optimize delivery and customer experience. Deliveries can be tracked in real time and items can be delivered to various locations, including a customer’s car trunk, or even by drones and robots.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;Smart store furniture and items (shelves, mirrors, baskets, etc.) (CX&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;IoT)&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The use of connected furniture or items can improve in-store customer experience and retail operations. Smart shelves notice when an item is picked up and can show product details on a display. Electronic shelf labeling is enabled by QR codes or NFC, which can be linked to mobile apps. Smart baskets detect the items placed in it and enable a self-checkout concept without cashiers. Digital mirrors enable digital clothes fitting.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;

&lt;section class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Selection of providers&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Providers are selected and invited according to the following criteria: &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul &gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Size of revenues&lt;/strong&gt; in the segment to be analyzed in the specified region &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;“Relevance”&lt;/strong&gt;: Even providers that do not belong to the top-selling providers in the segment to be analyzed are considered, if teknowlogy classifies them as relevant for potential customers, for instance due to an innovative offering, strong growth, or a compelling vision.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is no differentiation as to whether the providers are customers of teknowlogy – neither in the selection of the providers to be positioned, nor in the actual evaluation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The decision as to which providers are considered in the teknowlogy INNOVATION RADAR analysis is entirely up to teknowlogy. Providers do not have any direct influence on this decision. &lt;/p&gt;



&lt;h3&gt;Providers positioned in the segment of C&amp;amp;SI for IoT solutions for Smart Retail&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;CPG&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;ul &gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Accenture&lt;/strong&gt; has become a major provider of business and IT consulting Accenture positions itself as an end-to-end service provider to support its customers in their digital transformation by&quot;helping organizations maximize their performance and achieve their vision&quot;.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Atos&lt;/strong&gt; is a €12 billion revenue company with 100,000 employees in 72 countries. Atos conducts business through three service lines: consulting, systems integration and managed operations.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;BearingPoint&lt;/strong&gt; is a multinational management and technology consulting firm headquartered in Amsterdam, the Netherlands. It has operations in 35 countries with around 3,901 employees and is one of the largest management consultancies in Europe with an annual revenue. &lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Capgemini&lt;/strong&gt; is a France-based company and offers business consulting, functional&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;IT-oriented consulting, integration and development, outsourcing and BPO services in the country, both in the application and infrastructure fields.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CGI&lt;/strong&gt; is a Canadian IT consulting, systems integration, outsourcing and solutions company founded in 1976. Since the acquisition of Logica in 2012, CGI is the fifth-largest independent business processes and IT services provider in the world with approximately 70,000 members (the internal word for employees) across 40 countries.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cognizant&lt;/strong&gt; started out in 1994 as the technology arm of The Dun&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;Bradstreet Corporation. Today, its business units are aligned with digital solutions and services. The company is headquartered in Teaneck, New Jersey, and employs 260,200 people worldwide.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Deloitte&lt;/strong&gt; company network is made up of independent firms, owned and managed locally, members of global accounting powerhouse Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu Limited (DTTL). Deloitte's business is focused on five core areas: audit, consulting, financial advisory, enterprise risk services and tax&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;legal. The company has 263,900 employees and generated an annual revenue of USD 38.8 billion in 2017.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fujitsu&lt;/strong&gt; was created as a spin-off of the communications division of Fuji Electric Company. Fujitsu specializes in electronic devices, computing products, telecommunications products, software and IT services. Fujitsu employs 155,000 people across more than 100 countries. &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;IBM&lt;/strong&gt; is a global technology company, founded in 1911, that provides hardware, software, cloud-based services and cognitive computing. It is one of the world's largest employers, with over 380,000 employees in over 170 countries. &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Infosys&lt;/strong&gt; is an Indian multinational corporation, founded Infosys in 1981, that provides business consulting, information technology and outsourcing services. Infosys employs more than 200,000 people.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wipro Limited&lt;/strong&gt; (formerly Western India Products Limited) is an Indian multinational provider of IT services, consulting and outsourcing services. Wipro is now a truly global corporation with operations in over 70 countries and more than 170,000 employees. IT services are the biggest part of its business by far. &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
