&lt;div class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Teknowlogy Group Opinion&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
&lt;p &gt;Key findings&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For this RADAR report, we selected 11 major providers from a list of more than 20 C&amp;amp;SI players with a focus on retail and conducted a detailed analysis of their smart retail&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;CPG strategies, portfolios and strengths.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Quite generally, we see a rather homogeneous top-player landscape in smart retail&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;CPG C&amp;amp;SI, mainly consisting of large international and traditional IT services and technology companies. In addition, three Indian players were able to position themselves among the 11 top companies selected for our ranking (Infosys, Wipro, Cognizant).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Among the 11 companies with advanced C&amp;amp;SI capabilities in the smart retail&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;CPG area, three players were identified to be “Best in Class”: Accenture, IBM and Capgemini. These three have a strong retail-focused IT services practice and can therefore also be found among the top 5 providers in teknowlogy’s EMEA IT services ranking for the retail&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;wholesale sector. They are outstanding in providing a highly standardized set of C&amp;amp;SI services in the field of smart retail&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;CPG; this context being relatively recent, other players have not yet reached the same high level.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Even though Fujitsu is not (yet) among the top 3 companies according to the present retail&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;CPG RADAR results, we expect the company to secure a ranking among the top players in the short term. Due to the company’s broad and global retail know-how, its&quot;Connected Retail&quot; approach and ability to integrate end-to-end retail solutions into the large and complex IT landscapes of retail companies, Fujitsu has the potential to quickly enhance its RADAR positioning.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Most of the companies analyzed in this smart retail&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;CPG RADAR started their IoT-specific activities in the manufacturing area, where they built up know-how, partnerships and industrial IoT-specific laboratories, and then gradually transferred their IoT know-how and processes to the retail area. As a consequence, only very few C&amp;amp;SI players have retail-specific IoT centers or labs for the development and testing of complex smart retail use cases today; among those who do, we see e.g. Accenture (Future Store at Coop Italy in Milan), Atos (Retail Transformation Lab&quot;Store of the future&quot; in Amstelveen, the Netherlands) and CGI (center of excellence for retail and consumer services in Lille, France). However, teknowlogy expects more players to follow this approach. Among the strategies of the “Best in Class” players, Accenture’s Future Store in collaboration with Coop Italy is in fact outstanding, as it is not just a concept store or laboratory, but a real supermarket to shop in. Ideas like interactive display tables, innovative shelving options or real-time data visualization have already been brought into life.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In order to better enable their clients to meet the rapidly changing requirements of their customers and to quickly fill white spots in their portfolios, mergers&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;acquisitions are a popular strategy for many players in the smart retail&amp;nbsp;&amp;amp;&amp;nbsp;CPG area. Accenture, for example, recently took over Kurt Salmon (retail strategy consulting), dgroup (management consulting) and Javelin Group (retail strategy consulting and digital transformation services provider), while Infosys acquired Skava (provider of digital experience solutions for the retail industry) and Wipro bought Designit (strategic design company).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
